    <Data><![CDATA[<h2 style="font-family: 'Segoe UI', 'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; color: rgb(17, 17, 17);">Description</h2>
  <p style="font-family: 'Segoe UI', 'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: small; margin: 0.5em 0px 1em; padding: 0px; line-height: 1.5em; color: rgb(17, 17, 17);">Whenever information is transported over a communication channel, it is susceptible to Man-in-the-Middle (MITM) attacks. Information sent via HTTP is not protected during transport.&amp;nbsp; It is transmitted in clear text, and any attacker can intercept, read and manipulate it before it reaches the web server.&amp;nbsp;</p>
  <h2 style="font-family: 'Segoe UI', 'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; color: rgb(17, 17, 17);">Impact</h2>
  <p style="font-family: 'Segoe UI', 'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: small; margin: 0.5em 0px 1em; padding: 0px; line-height: 1.5em; color: rgb(17, 17, 17);">Information sent over HTTP is transmitted in clear text and vulnerable to MITM attacks which can lead to theft of sensitive information.</p>
  <h2 style="font-family: 'Segoe UI', 'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; color: rgb(17, 17, 17);">Countermeasures</h2>
  <p>Send information only via a secure channel such as SSL/TLS.&amp;nbsp;All sensitive information must be sent over SSL/TLS during 
authentication and all subsequent request too must be over secure channel to avoid exposing data and session IDs to 
interception. The certificates should be signed by a trusted third party certificate authority&amp;nbsp;and the validity period should always be correct during the course of usage on the site.</p>
  <p>Play Framework supports SSL since Play Framework v1.1.1 onwards.&amp;nbsp;It supports certificate management, either via the classical Java keystore or simple cert and key files. <br /></p>
  <p>To start an HTTPS connector for your application:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>The&amp;nbsp; <font face="Courier New">https.port</font>&amp;nbsp; parameter must be configured property in your&amp;nbsp; <font face="Courier New">application.conf</font>&amp;nbsp; file.</li>
    <li>The certificates must be placed in the&amp;nbsp; <font face="Courier New">conf</font>&amp;nbsp; directory. <br /></li>
    <li>Proper key management must be in place.</li>
    <li>Older SSL versions (<_3d_sslv229_26_nbsp3b_should not="" be="" supported.=""></_3d_sslv229_26_nbsp3b_should><br /></li>
    <li>Care must be taken that the application should not redirect back to&amp;nbsp; <font face="Courier New">http</font>&amp;nbsp; when the&amp;nbsp; <font face="Courier New">https</font>&amp;nbsp; connection fails. <br /></li>
    <li>All sensitive information must be sent only via SSL/TLS.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Detailed information on setting up HTTPS support on Play Framework for Scala using Play's built-in support may be found <a href="http://www.playframework.com/documentation/1.2.3/production#https">here</a>.&amp;nbsp;</p>
  <p>If you are using a front-end server, set up a reverse proxy. Information on setting up a reverse proxy may be found <a href="http://www.playframework.com/documentation/1.2.3/production#https">here</a>.</p>
